						<div class="verses">
									<div id="vers152555" class="vers vers-inline">
												<div class="vers-no">1</div>
						<div class="vers-content">Then David mustered anew the fighting men of Israel, thirty thousand strong.<span class="content-paragraph"><br><br></span></div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers152556" class="vers vers-inline">
												<div class="vers-no">2</div>
						<div class="vers-content">Meanwhile, he set out with the men of Juda that followed him, and went to fetch the ark of God home; that ark which takes its name from the Lord God of hosts, dwelling there above it between the cherubim.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers152557" class="vers vers-inline">
												<div class="vers-no">3</div>
						<div class="vers-content">And they carried the ark away from Abinadabâs house at Gabaa, putting it on a newly-made waggon, with Abinadabâs sons, Oza and Ahio, for its drivers.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers152558" class="vers vers-inline">
												<div class="vers-no">4</div>
						<div class="vers-content">He it was had had charge of it, there in Gabaa, till now; but now they took it away from his house, with Ahio walking before it,</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers152559" class="vers vers-inline">
												<div class="vers-no">5</div>
						<div class="vers-content">while David and the Israelites played music, there in the Lordâs presence, on instruments of rare workmanship, harp and zither and tambour and castanets and cymbals.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers152560" class="vers vers-inline">
												<div class="vers-no">6</div>
						<div class="vers-content">They had reached the threshing-floor of Nachon, when the oxen began to kick and tilted the ark to one side; whereupon Oza put out his hand and caught hold of it.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers152561" class="vers vers-inline">
												<div class="vers-no">7</div>
						<div class="vers-content">Rash deed of his, that provoked the divine anger; the Lord smote him, and he died there beside the ark.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers152562" class="vers vers-inline">
												<div class="vers-no">8</div>
						<div class="vers-content">Great grief it was to David, this ruin the Lord had brought on Oza (the place is still called Ozaâs Ruin),</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers152563" class="vers vers-inline">
												<div class="vers-no">9</div>
						<div class="vers-content">and a dread of the Lord came upon him that day; How shall I, he asked, give shelter to the Lordâs ark?</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers152564" class="vers vers-inline">
												<div class="vers-no">10</div>
						<div class="vers-content">No longer was he minded to give it a lodging in Davidâs Keep; it must find a home with Obededom the Gethite instead.<span class="content-paragraph"><br><br></span></div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers152565" class="vers vers-inline">
												<div class="vers-no">11</div>
						<div class="vers-content">For three months the ark of the Lord was left with Obededom the Gethite, and brought a blessing on him and his household.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers152566" class="vers vers-inline">
												<div class="vers-no">12</div>
						<div class="vers-content">Then word was brought to David how the Lord had blessed Obededom and all that was his for the arkâs sake. So back he went, and brought the ark of God away from Obededomâs house, into Davidâs Keep, with great rejoicing; seven choirs of dancers he took with him, and a young bull for a victim.<a href="" class="inline-comment" data-comment-id="456">â»</a></div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers152567" class="vers vers-inline">
												<div class="vers-no">13</div>
						<div class="vers-content">No sooner had the bearers of the ark gone six paces on their journey, than he sacrificed the bull and a ram with it.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers152568" class="vers vers-inline">
												<div class="vers-no">14</div>
						<div class="vers-content">As for himself, he went dancing with all his might, there in the Lordâs presence; clad in the sacred mantle, he must dance too.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers152569" class="vers vers-inline">
												<div class="vers-no">15</div>
						<div class="vers-content">So David, and Israel with him, brought back the ark that bears record of the Lordâs covenant, with rejoicing and a great din of trumpets.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers152570" class="vers vers-inline">
												<div class="vers-no">16</div>
						<div class="vers-content">And as it came into Davidâs Keep, there was Michol, Saulâs daughter, looking on from her window; she saw king David leaping and dancing in the Lordâs presence, and her heart despised him.<span class="content-paragraph"><br><br></span></div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers152571" class="vers vers-inline">
												<div class="vers-no">17</div>
						<div class="vers-content">When the ark had been brought into the city, they put it down at the appointed place, in the midst of a tabernacle which David had there spread out for it; and David brought burnt-sacrifices and welcome-offerings into the Lordâs presence there.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers152572" class="vers vers-inline">
												<div class="vers-no">18</div>
						<div class="vers-content">Then, when his offering was done, he blessed the people in the name of the Lord of hosts,</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers152573" class="vers vers-inline">
												<div class="vers-no">19</div>
						<div class="vers-content">and gave to every Israelite, man or woman, a roll of bread and a piece of roast beef and a flour cake fried in oil;<a href="" class="inline-comment" data-comment-id="457">â»</a> and with that, the people dispersed to their homes.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers152574" class="vers vers-inline">
												<div class="vers-no">20</div>
						<div class="vers-content">David himself, going back to bless his own household, was met by Michol, Saulâs daughter. A day of great renown, she said, for the king of Israel, that exposed his person to man and maid, his own subjects, graceless as a common mountebank!</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers152575" class="vers vers-inline">
												<div class="vers-no">21</div>
						<div class="vers-content">Nay, answered David, it was at the Lordâs coming. He it is that has chosen me, instead of thy father or any of thy fatherâs line, to rule the Lordâs people of Israel;</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers152576" class="vers vers-inline">
												<div class="vers-no">22</div>
						<div class="vers-content">and before his coming play the mountebank I will; humble myself I will in my own esteem, and those maids thou speakest of will honour me yet the more.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers152577" class="vers vers-inline">
												<div class="vers-no">23</div>
						<div class="vers-content">And Michol, that was daughter to king Saul, never bore child again to the day of her death.<span class="content-paragraph"><br><br></span></div>
					</div>
